<worksheet xml:id="activities-counting">

<activity>

	<introduction><p> A standard Alberta license plate has three letters followed by three or four digits. </p></introduction>

	<task><p> How many different vehicles can the province license with this scheme? </p></task>

	<task>

		<statement><p>
			Do you think the province was right to expand license plates by adding another digit,
			or do you think it should have added another letter instead?
			(Or, as a third possibility, is it irrelevant in practical terms?)
		</p></statement>

		<hint><p> The figure <m> {26}^3 = 17576 </m> may help you decide. </p></hint>

	</task>

</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-counting-roll-die">

	<task xml:id="activity-counting-roll-die-ten-times"><p>
		You roll a six-sided die ten times.
		How many different sequences of rolls are possible?
	</p></task>

	<task><p>
		Describe how <xref ref="activity-counting-roll-die-ten-times" text="type-local" />
		relates to the problem of determining <m> \card{\words{\Sigma}_{10}} </m> for a suitable alphabet <m> \Sigma </m>.
	</p></task>

</activity>

<activity><p>
	Let <m> \Sigma = \EngAlphabet </m>.
	How many words in <m> \words{\Sigma}_5 </m> end in the letter <m> z </m>?
	How many do not?
</p></activity>

<activity><p>
	You and your five housemates pick names out of a hat each week to determine who is going to clean the toilet.
	Over a three-week period, how many different sequences of toilet bowl cleaners could be determined in this fashion
	<ol marker="(i)">
		<li> if names are placed back in the hat after each draw? </li>
		<li> if names are <em>not</em> placed back in the hat after each draw? </li>
	</ol>
</p></activity>

<activity>

	<statement><p> How many natural numbers between <m> 1 </m> and <m> 1,000,000 </m> (inclusive) contain the digit <m> 5 </m>? </p></statement>

	<hint><p> You might instead count how many numbers <em>don't</em> contain the digit <m> 5 </m>. </p></hint>

</activity>

<activity>

	<statement><p>
		How many natural numbers between <m> 100 </m> and <m> 999 </m> (inclusive) have no repeated digits?
		Of these, how many are odd?
	</p></statement>

	<hint><p> There's no rule that when you <q>construct</q> an arbitrary object of this type that you have to choose the first digit first. </p></hint>

</activity>

<activity>

	<statement><p>
		Use the <xref ref="corollary-counting-pigeon" text="title" />
		to prove that in every set of three integers there exists a pair whose difference is even.
	</p></statement>

	<hint><p> What kinds of numbers add up to an even sum? </p></hint>

</activity>

<activity><p>
	You have a list of the names of twenty students.
	Ten of the students are domestic students and the other ten are out-of-province students.
	How many students must you select from the list to be certain to form a group that contains at least one domestic student and at least one out-of-province student?
</p></activity>

<activity><p>
	Let <m> n </m> be a fixed natural number.
	Determine the smallest number <m> M </m> for which the following statement is true:
	every subset of <md> \natnumlt{2n + 1} = \{0,1,2,3,\dotsc,2n\} </md>
	of size <m> M </m> contains at least one odd number.
</p></activity>

<activity>

	<introduction><p>
		You're cleaning up your little nephew's toy room.
		There are <m> T </m> toys on the floor and <m> n </m> empty toy storage boxes.
		You randomly throw toys into boxes, and when you're done the box with the most toys contains <m> N </m> toys.
	</p></introduction>

	<task><p> What is the smallest that <m> N </m> could be when <m> T = 2 n + 1 </m>? </p></task>

	<task><p> What is the smallest that <m> N </m> could be when <m> T = k n + 1 </m>? </p></task>

	<task>

		<statement>

			<p> Now suppose that the number of toys <m> T </m> satisfies <m>\displaystyle T \lt \frac{n (n - 1)}{2} </m>. </p>

			<p> Prove that when you are done cleaning up, there will be (at least) one pair of boxes that contain the same number of toys. </p>

		</statement>

		<hint><p>
			Argue the contrapositive by assuming that every box ends up a different number of toys.
			What is the <em>fewest</em> number of toys you could have started with?
		</p></hint>

	</task>

</activity>

</worksheet>
